Willie's has good chicken fingers. My husband and I stopped by this location while waiting for our swamp tour bus to pick us up. It was right up the street from our hotel on Bourbon. They serve fried chicken hence the name Chicken Shack. Their chicken finders were actually pretty good. My husband and I shared a 3 piece Cajun style chicken finger plate. We got fries and a biscuit. The chicken tenders were spicy hence the name "Cajun style". They were so good with BBQ and Honey Mustard Sauce. They also made our chicken fingers fresh but it took literally like 20-25 min. Luckily, we were the first stop that the tour bus stopped at. The bus waited a few minutes. The bus literally had to pull up right in front of Willies for my husband to catch the bus. I had to walk back to the hotel and catch it there so we could hold our spot.  However, their jambalaya was just meh. It had a good flavor but it tasted a day old. It literally tasted like they just pulled it out the fridge and heated it up. It was not fresh at all. The chicken tasted "reheated". They use their fried chicken in the jambalaya. It added a nice crunch but it wasn't what I was use to.  Overall, Willie's has good chicken fingers. If you go I would suggest getting the chicken fingers or chicken. It will be fresh although you may wait a little minute. I would recommend having a few minutes to wait.

These joints literally litter the French Quarters of New Orleans. For all of my many, many visits over the past 5 - 10’years I passed by them really for no reason. So, one night stumbling (metaphor) back too my room. I stopped in. First the cashier was hilarious. Somehow, being mid 20’s and growing up native she’d seen it all.  Typical greasy spoon with decent chicken and fixings. Surprisingly, the chicken was tasty or either I had one too many hurricanes. In realty I was pleasantly surprised at the crunchiness of the chicken and the fact that it was thoroughly cooked. Definitely a plus on that one. Not  flavorful (seasoned) but palatable and tasty. I wish I had my Texas Pete but settled for Louisiana Hot Sauce.  In any case, I’m going to make it a point to frequent these joints on the run. I notice not all of them exhibited the same cleanliness and that was a problem. But it’s the quarters and my standards are generally middle of the road. Either way New Orleans will always be a special destination.  So, yeah give Willies a try!
